### 5. Cross-Task Insights — The Dual-Model Advantage (Team)
 
Both tasks reveal a consistent theme: **location is the most important structural feature in NYC taxi data.** Where a trip starts and ends determines both how long it will take (via traffic patterns and distance) and whether it incurs congestion fees (via CBD zone boundaries). Temporal features (hour, day of week, rush hour) add a meaningful second layer of signal, particularly for trip duration.
 
The consistent superiority of Random Forest over linear models across both tasks demonstrates that NYC taxi behavior involves significant non-linear interactions — a trip from JFK at 5 PM behaves very differently from a trip within Manhattan at the same time, and tree-based models capture these interactions without explicit feature engineering.
 
**What makes our approach novel**, as identified in our stakeholder analysis, is twofold: (1) we use post-congestion pricing data from January 2025 — all prior ML work on NYC taxi data (e.g., the 2016 Kaggle competition) predates the policy and cannot analyze fee patterns, and (2) we combine duration prediction with fee exposure prediction into a dual-model system that enables the kind of profitability calculation Maria needs, rather than treating each prediction task in isolation.
 
